    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
            <summary>What is a Wingdings translator?</summary>
            <p>A Wingdings translator is a tool that converts standard text (like English letters and numbers) into the symbol-based Wingdings font, or translates Wingdings symbols back into readable text.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>How do you translate standard text into Wingdings?</summary>
            <p>You can translate text by typing it into a Wingdings translator tool, which automatically maps each standard character to its designated symbol in the Wingdings character set.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Are there different versions of Wingdings?</summary>
            <p>Yes, Microsoft released several versions, including Wingdings, Wingdings 2, Wingdings 3, and Webdings, each featuring a completely different set of symbols and character mappings.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Why was Wingdings created in the first place?</summary>
            <p>Wingdings was created in the early 1990s to give users an easy way to insert high-quality, scalable symbols and icons into their documents using just a keyboard, before inserting images was a seamless process.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Is Wingdings the same thing as an emoji?</summary>
            <p>No. While similar in concept, Wingdings are font-specific symbols mapped to standard keyboard keys. Emojis use standardized Unicode points, making them universally recognizable across different systems and fonts.</p>
        </details>
    </section>
